Here is an example of a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:
```
#include <string>
#include <regex>
#include <iostream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
  // Replace Markdown headers with HTML headers
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^# (.*)$"), "<h1>$1</h1>");
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^## (.*)$"), "<h2>$1</h2>");
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^### (.*)$"), "<h3>$1</h3>");

  // Replace Markdown bold text with HTML bold text
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("(**)([^]*?)\\1"), "<b>$2</b>");

  // Replace Markdown italic text with HTML italic text
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("(*)([^]*?)\\1"), "<i>$2</i>");

  // Replace Markdown links with HTML links
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("([(http|https)://[^\(\)]*)"), "<a href=\"$1\">$1</a>");

  // Replace Markdown images with HTML images
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("!\[(.*?)\]\((.*)\)", std::regex::ECMAScript), "<img src=\"$2\" alt=\"$1\">");

  // Replace Markdown code blocks with HTML code blocks
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("```([^]*?)```"), "<pre><code>$1</code></pre>");

  // Replace newlines and tabs with HTML breaks
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("\n"), "<br>");
  markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("\t"), "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;");

  return markdown;
}
```
This function uses the `std::regex` class to search for and replace Markdown patterns with their corresponding HTML equivalents.

Please note that this is a very basic implementation and may not cover all possible Markdown syntax. You may need to add more logic to handle more complex Markdown features.

Also, this function assumes that the input Markdown text does not contain any invalid or unescaped characters that could cause issues with the HTML output. In a real-world application, you would want to add error checking and handling for such cases.

